  2. Ham Sandwich Forum Resident

    Location:
    Sherwood, OR, USA
    I use SoX. SoX does the best sounding digital de-emphasis to me of the options I've tried. I do archive the original pre-emphasis files so if I do find a method that sounds better than SoX I can go redo my pre-emphasis files using the new tool.

    My method:
    Rip to a single WAV with a CUE file using EAC
    Run that WAV file through SoX to do de-emphasis
    Manually edit the CUE file using a text editor to point to the de-emphasized WAV file
    Split the WAV and CUE to separate tracks using CUETools and convert to FLAC
    Import the FLAC files to my music library
     
    Ham Sandwich, Apr 2, 2017

  3. Arnold_Layne Forum Resident

    Location:
    Waldorf, MD USA
    I have a batch file that will do the deemphasis for you without having to create cue files, and do renaming etc. It will work with WAVE and FLAC files.

    Put the following text into notepad then save as a .bat file to the SoX directory. You can create a shortcut to the .bat on the desktop, then drag and drop files to the .bat shortcut. The new files will be in a folder called "Converted" in the "SoX" directory.

    cd %~dp0
    mkdir converted
    FOR %%A IN (%*) DO sox %%A "converted/%%~nxA" deemph
    pause
     
    Arnold_Layne, Apr 2, 2017

  15. Ham Sandwich Forum Resident

    Location:
    Sherwood, OR, USA
    Emospence said: ↑
    Is it safe to say it won't be possible to replicate the result of a CD player?
    Click to expand...
    It is possible to replicate the result of a CD player. But depends on the particular CD player.

    Pre-emphasis is done with an analog circuit before the AD converter. Early CD players did de-emphasis with an analog circuit after the DA converter. Later CD players started doing the conversion digitally. Some DAC chips have a de-emphasis feature as part of the DAC chip itself.

    We aren't going to exactly match an analog circuit and its sound with a digitally done de-emphasis. Analog is going to sound different than digital. We can match, and possibly even exceed, the results of a CD player that did the de-emphasis digitally.
     
    Ham Sandwich, Apr 3, 2017
    #15

  19. Ham Sandwich Forum Resident

    Location:
    Sherwood, OR, USA
    Are you able to open a command prompt. Type sox and have sox run?

    The regular install of SoX doesn't add the SoX directory to the system PATH. Which means if you type "sox" at the command prompt you'll get an error saying "sox is not recognized as an internal or external command...".

    So first step will be adding the sox directory to the PATH so you can more easily run sox from the command line.

    I'm assuming Windows 10 for these steps. Windows 8 or 7 will be slightly different.

    Open Control Panel
    Go to System
    On the left in the System window will be an option for "Advanced system settings"
    click on "Advanced system settings"
    Go to the "Advanced" tab
    Click on the Environment Variables... button
    Under System variables select the Path variable and then click the "Edit..." button
    That will open up the Edit environment variables dialog
    Click the "New" button to add a new directory to the path
    Enter the directory where SoX is installed. Likely "C:\Program Files (x86)\sox-14-4-2"
    Click OK to close the dialog

    Now open a new command prompt and type sox.

    That should cause sox to run and display its help text telling you all the command line options you can use.

    Once you get SoX to run to that point we can move on.
     
    Ham Sandwich, Jul 1, 2017

    It's not a good idea to be filling the Windows directory full of utility files. That's bad form, and is a bad way to manage a windows install.

    The right way is to add the SoX folder and other utility folders to the PATH. The Sox installer should have done that, but it doesn't. So we're left to do it manually. I really wish SoX would add its folder to the PATH because that would make it much easier for non-techies to run and use the program.

    Rather than dumping utility files in the Windows folder you should make a bin folder somewhere like "C:\bin" or "C:\Program Files (x86)\bin". Add that bin folder to the path and then dump all your utilities in that bin folder.

  1. Ham Sandwich Forum Resident

    Location:
    Sherwood, OR, USA
    Batears52 said: ↑
    This worked - I got SoX to run using this method. I'll pick this up tomorrow for the next steps.
    Click to expand...
    For the next steps I'll assume the rip is named "album.cue" and "album.wav".

    Open a command prompt and navigate to the folder where you rip is

    The sox command to do de-emphasis is: sox [input file] [output file] deemph

    For this example you will run the command
    sox "album.wav" "album (deemph).wav" deemph

    That will create a new file named "album (deepmh).wav"

    Open "album.cue" in a text editor
    find the line in the CUE files that says: FILE "album.wav" WAVE
    change that line to: FILE "album (deemph).wav" WAVE
    save the edited CUE file to a file named "album (deemph).cue"

    Next step will be to open that new CUE file in CUETools and split it to separate tracks
    I'll explain how to do that in the next post
     
    Ham Sandwich, Jul 2, 2017

  2. Ham Sandwich Forum Resident

    Location:
    Sherwood, OR, USA
    Download CUETools_2.1.5.zip from here: CUETools Download - CUETools wiki
    CUETools doesn't have an installer program.
    Extract the ZIP file to a directory
    Manually launch CUETools by double-clicking on "CUETools.exe"

    Input file will be "album (deemph).cue"
    Output file will be where the split out files get saved

    Action: set this to "Encode"
    Mode: set this to "Tracks"
    Audio Output: set this to "Lossless" and select the lossless format you want (default is flac)

    Click the "Go" button
     
    Ham Sandwich, Jul 2, 2017

  6. acdc7369 Forum Resident

    Location:
    Pittsburgh
    I have yet to see someone properly explain how to do this in Sox.

    1. Create a Cue sheet of the album.
    2. Rip the entire album as a single .wav file at 32 (or 24) bit.
    3. De-emphasize the file with Sox.
    4. Load the de-emphasized file into a .wav editing program.
    5. Normalize the file to 0 dBFS and save.
    6. Break up the .wav file into individual tracks based on the cue sheet.
    7. Optional: if you must, use Foobar to downconvert the tracks to 16-bit.

    If the black triangle Abbey Road is one of the albums you're doing, in between steps 4 and 5:
    1. Invert the polarity of both channels.
    2. One of the channels (I forget which) is exactly one sample behind the other channel, which will cause phase/imaging issues. Fix it by cutting and pasting one of the channels a sample ahead of where it was.
     
    acdc7369, Jul 3, 2017
    #31

    That disc does have pre emphasis. Tag is probably located in the SUB Q channel. CR is probably not detecting it because certain drives won't work.
    I have 1 that does, two that won't.
    Did you try EAC at least for table of contents? If it doesn't show it's in the SUB.
    Jay have you been able to verify other titles SUBQ with Cue Ripper?
